<header class="hero" id="how">
  <div><div class="eyebrow">Internal mission brief · final v1</div><h1>The World’s Prediction Markets Summit.<br/>Built by <em>owners</em>.</h1>
  <p class="lead">This deck is the working GTM for NEXTPredict 2026. Everyone reads the shared mission, scoreboard, rules and critical path. Then each owner reads their own playbook. The objective is simple: faster action, clearer handoffs, stronger reporting and fewer approval bottlenecks.</p></div>
  <aside class="hero-card"><h2 style="margin:0 0 14px;font-size:16px;color:#fff;">How to use this deck</h2><div class="stat-grid">
    <div class="stat"><b>1</b><span>Everyone reads shared context</span></div><div class="stat"><b>2</b><span>Each owner reads their playbook</span></div><div class="stat"><b>3</b><span>Use decision rights to move</span></div><div class="stat"><b>4</b><span>Escalate exceptions early</span></div>
  </div><div class="callout">This is not a “read everything” document. It is a role-based execution system.</div></aside>
</header>

<section id="mission">
  <div class="section-head"><div><div class="kicker">01 · Mission and positioning</div><h2 class="section-title">The strategic decision is made</h2></div><p class="section-note">The team should stop debating what NEXTPredict is and start translating the position into pages, campaigns, content, sales conversations and delivery.</p></div>
  <div class="grid-4">
    <div class="card gold"><div class="label">Why now</div><h3>The category is forming in public</h3><p>Prediction markets and event contracts are moving from niche conversation to institutional, regulatory, operator, product and capital-market relevance. The window to define the serious version of the category is open now.</p></div>
    <div class="card blue"><div class="label">Why NEXT.io</div><h3>We have unfair infrastructure</h3><p>NEXT.io already has event delivery, media capability, senior relationships, commercial experience and scars from complex launches. This team can credibly seize the category moment.</p></div>
    <div class="card green"><div class="label">Positioning</div><h3>Wall Street first</h3><p>Keep finance, trading, event contracts, compliance and infrastructure language ahead of iGaming. Operators are relevant through product learning, partnership access and category intelligence.</p></div>
    <div class="card red"><div class="label">What it is not</div><h3>Not a betting conference</h3><p>Not an iGaming expo, crypto hype event, retail trading show, legal seminar, startup demo day or sportsbook conference.</p></div>
  </div>
  <div class="callout">Mission line: <strong>We are not promoting a conference. We are building the institutional meeting point for a category before others dilute it.</strong></div>
</section>

<section id="winning">
  <div class="section-head"><div><div class="kicker">02 · What winning looks like</div><h2 class="section-title">Give the team a destination</h2></div><p class="section-note">Targets matter. But teams execute harder when they can see the room they are building.</p></div>
  <div class="card gold"><p style="font-size:18px;line-height:1.75;color:#f3ead7;">On 22 October, success looks like a buyer-dense room in New York: operators, platforms, legal experts, data providers, investors and market-infrastructure leaders in the same conversations. Sponsors are getting the meetings they paid for. Speakers are validating the category. Media is capturing proof for 2027. HPL is amplifying real momentum, not manufactured hype. Oli can point to the paid audience mix with confidence. Will is already opening renewal conversations before the room clears. That is the win.</p></div>
</section>

<section id="scoreboard">
  <div class="section-head"><div><div class="kicker">03 · Commercial scoreboard</div><h2 class="section-title">The numbers must never be blended</h2></div><p class="section-note">Paid tickets, free operator tickets, sponsor passes and comps are different things. Blended reporting will make the event look healthier than it is.</p></div>
  <div class="grid-4">
    <div class="card gold"><div class="label">Paid-ticket target</div><h3>1,000</h3><p><strong>Owner:</strong> Oli. Paid tickets only. Free operator tickets, comps, sponsor passes and speaker guests do not count.</p></div>
    <div class="card blue"><div class="label">Net paid-ticket revenue</div><h3>€1.25M</h3><p><strong>Owner:</strong> Stuart + Oli + Finance. Average realised price, FX, VAT/tax, Bizzabo/card fees, refunds and discounts affect this.</p></div>
    <div class="card orange"><div class="label">B2B partnerships</div><h3>€1.35M</h3><p><strong>Owner:</strong> Will. Closed Won, weighted pipeline, stuck deals and sponsor concentration risk are reviewed weekly.</p></div>
    <div class="card green"><div class="label">Free operator tickets</div><h3>TBC</h3><p><strong>Owner:</strong> Rory’s team + Stuart. Tracked separately from paid-ticket target and revenue. Counts toward room quality where appropriate.</p></div>
  </div>
  <div class="matrix" style="margin-top:16px;"><table><thead><tr><th>Metric</th><th>Definition</th><th>Escalation trigger</th><th>Owner response</th></tr></thead><tbody>
    <tr><td><strong>Buyer-density ratio</strong></td><td>Institutional buyers / total classified attendees.</td><td>Below 65% at any phase gate.</td><td>Stuart changes acquisition mix even if paid-ticket volume is on track.</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Supplier-risk percentage</strong></td><td>Supplier/vendor attendees / total classified attendees.</td><td>Supplier share rising faster than institutional buyer share.</td><td>Reduce low-value supplier acquisition; increase operator/platform/institutional outreach.</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Unknown classification rate</strong></td><td>Unclassified attendees / total attendees.</td><td>Too high to support sponsor proof.</td><td>Manual classification sprint owned by Oli/Jo.</td></tr>
  </tbody></table></div>
</section>

<section id="value">
  <div class="section-head"><div><div class="kicker">04 · Value proposition and vocabulary</div><h2 class="section-title">Why buyers and sponsors should care</h2></div><p class="section-note">NEXTPredict solves a market-coordination problem: the people shaping prediction markets are fragmented across finance, regulation, operators, exchanges, data, legal, media and capital.</p></div>
  <div class="grid-4">
    <div class="card gold"><div class="label">Attendees</div><h3>Market clarity</h3><p>The category is moving quickly and the signal is fragmented. NEXTPredict gives attendees one concentrated room to understand the market, meet decision-makers and benchmark thinking.</p></div>
    <div class="card blue"><div class="label">Sponsors</div><h3>Category ownership</h3><p>Sponsors need access to a new buyer category before the market gets crowded. NEXTPredict gives visible position, buyer access, meeting opportunities and proof assets.</p></div>
    <div class="card green"><div class="label">Operators</div><h3>Strategic learning</h3><p>Operators need to understand event contracts without gambling-adjacent hype. NEXTPredict gives product, compliance, partnership and commercial intelligence.</p></div>
    <div class="card purple"><div class="label">Investors</div><h3>Early signal</h3><p>Capital needs thesis development before consensus forms. NEXTPredict gives access to founders, exchanges, data providers and infrastructure companies.</p></div>
  </div>
  <div class="matrix" style="margin-top:16px;"><table><thead><tr><th>Use</th><th>Avoid</th><th>Owner enforcing</th></tr></thead><tbody>
    <tr><td><strong>Prediction markets</strong>, event contracts, information markets, market integrity, compliance architecture, liquidity/infrastructure, institutional summit.</td><td>Betting markets, gambling disruption, bet on anything, crypto casino, regulatory loophole, sportsbook conference, iGaming expo.</td><td>HPL, Media, Rory, Stuart, Will and Oli.</td></tr>
  </tbody></table></div>
  <div class="callout red"><strong>Banned creative drift:</strong> no casino language, no “bet on everything,” no gambling-disruption framing, no unapproved DraftKings/Kalshi proximity, no public claims that cannot be supported.</div>
</section>

<section id="rules">
  <div class="section-head"><div><div class="kicker">05 · Decision rights and escalation</div><h2 class="section-title">Move fast inside the rules</h2></div><p class="section-note">Stuart should not be the first approver for routine execution. Owners move within agreed lanes. Exceptions escalate early.</p></div>
  <div class="matrix"><table><thead><tr><th>Owner</th><th>Can move without Stuart</th><th>Escalate when</th></tr></thead><tbody>
    <tr><td><strong>Oli</strong></td><td>Standard Founder/Early/Standard discount codes; bulk paid-ticket orders up to 9; non-late abandoned checkout recovery; Bizzabo code-usage reporting.</td><td>Outside discount ladder, 10+ ticket order, late recovery code, comp request without valid reason, sensitive account.</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Will</strong></td><td>Standard-package proposals; approved sweetener menu; sponsor ticket allocations within agreed Sponsor Ticket Bank; sales-team assignment and pipeline management.</td><td>Off-menu sweetener, non-standard terms, discount outside deal desk, sensitive account, buyer-density-impacting sponsor ticket request.</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Olivia</strong></td><td>Contracted sponsor deliverables; Monday.com handoff confirmation; delivery workflow management.</td><td>Request is outside contracted scope, unclear, sensitive, operationally unplanned or commercially risky.</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Jo</strong></td><td>Routine HubSpot forms; Bizzabo ↔ HubSpot integration work; approved field mapping and reporting setup.</td><td>Structural HubSpot change, new lifecycle logic, consent/compliance concern, field architecture change.</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Event Ops owner · TBC</strong></td><td>Bizzabo build/configuration within approved commercial and buyer-journey specs.</td><td>Ticket buyer journey, form fields, pricing logic or integration requirement is unclear.</td></tr>
  </tbody></table></div>
  <div class="callout">Escalation is not failure. Silence is failure. Launch blockers should be raised same day, not saved for the next weekly meeting.</div>
</section>

<section id="path">
  <div class="section-head"><div><div class="kicker">06 · Critical path</div><h2 class="section-title">27 May to 22 October</h2></div><p class="section-note">The event is won week by week. Each week needs shipped work, numbers, owner actions and escalations — not vague “progress made.”</p></div>

  <div class="grid-5" style="margin-bottom:18px;">
    <div class="dash"><span>Before 27 May</span><b>Gate</b><small>journey, build, integration, codes, tracking</small></div>
    <div class="dash"><span>19 Jun</span><b>100</b><small>cumulative paid tickets</small></div>
